Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Spencer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): occupational name for someone who dispensed provisions or money, from Middle English <i>spenser(e)</i>, <i>spencer(e)</i> ‘household steward, butler, almoner’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>espenser</i>, Old French <i>despensier</i>). Compare   Spence   and   Spender  . There is some dispute about the origins of the Spencer family, whose most famous member in recent times was the late Princess of Wales, born Lady Diana Spencer (1961–97). Some sources say that they are descended from William the Conqueror's steward, Robert Despencer. What is clear is that by the 15th century they had become prosperous from sheep farming in Northamptonshire. Robert Spencer (died 1627) was said to be the wealthiest man in England. Their titles have included Earls of Sunderland and Earls Spencer; and through the female line the 5th Earl of Sunderland also became Duke of Marlborough in 1733. This connection was the result of the marriage, in 1700, of the 3rd Duke of Sunderland to the daughter of John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough. The youngest son of this union, John Spencer (1708–46), was the father of the 1st Earl Spencer (1734–83)."],"variants":[{"name":"Spence","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a servant employed in the pantry of a great house or monastery, from Middle English <i>spense</i>, <i>spence</i> ‘pantry, larder, storeroom’ (Old French <i>despense</i>, from a Late Latin derivative of <i>dispendere</i>, past participle <i>dispensus</i> ‘to weigh out or dispense’). Compare   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spenser","meanings":["English: variant of   Spencer  ."]},{"name":"Spender","meanings":["English:","occupational name or status name from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘steward, treasurer’, a shortened form of Middle English, Old French <i>despendour</i>, denoting someone who managed money or supplies. Compare   Spencer  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>spender(e)</i>, <i>spendour</i> ‘spender (of money), spendthrift’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord John De Spencer was born about 1290, in Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir William Despencer and Anne de Lou. He had at least 1 son with Lady Alice Elizabeth Deverell. He died after 1386, in his hometown, and was buried in Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1290–AFT 1386":"umbes 1290–pärast 1386","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","1326–1432":"1326–1432","–Male":"Surnud","1235–1299":"1235–1299","AFT 1386":"pärast 1386","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1235":"1235","1432":"1432","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"umbes 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Defford, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Defford, Worcestershire, England":"Defford, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1290–AFT 1386":"noin 1290–1386 jälkeen","1290–1386":"1290–1386","1305–1386":"1305–1386","1326–1432":"1326–1432","–Male":"Kuollut","1235–1299":"1235–1299","AFT 1386":"1386 jälkeen","1305":"1305","1326":"1326","1235":"1235","1432":"1432","1299":"1299","1386":"1386","ABT 1290":"noin 1290","1290":"1290","Defford, Wor